  "prompt": "What is the difference between FRS, PRD, TRD, SRS, MRD, BRD?",
  "response": "In the context of product development, particularly in software engineering and project management, several documents are used to outline various aspects of a project. Here's a breakdown of the acronyms you've mentioned:\n\n1. **FRS (Functional Requirements Specification)**:\n   - This document describes the functions that a system or product must perform. It outlines the specific behavior and capabilities the system should have, including inputs, outputs, and interactions. FRS focuses on the \"what\" of a system.\n\n2. **PRD (Product Requirements Document)**:\n   - A comprehensive document that outlines the requirements for a product from a high-level perspective. It includes the vision, objectives, target audience, and key features of the product. The PRD serves as a guiding document for stakeholders and is used to communicate what the product should achieve.\n\n3. **TRD (Technical Requirements Document)**:\n   - This document focuses on the technical aspects and constraints of a project. It typically includes details about system architecture, technology stack, performance requirements, and non-functional requirements like scalability and security. TRD is used to ensure the technical feasibility and address technical considerations.\n\n4. **SRS (Software Requirements Specification)**:\n   - Similar to an FRS, the SRS is more comprehensive and includes both functional and non-functional requirements of the software. It serves as a contract between stakeholders and developers, detailing all aspects of what the software should do and any constraints on its operation.\n\n5. **MRD (Market Requirements Document)**:\n   - This document focuses on the market needs and opportunities that a product is intended to address. It includes analysis of the target market, competitive landscape, user personas, and needs assessment, helping to align product development with market demands.\n\n6. **BRD (Business Requirements Document)**:\n   - A document that outlines the high-level business needs and objectives that a project aims to address. It provides a framework for understanding the strategic goals and business context of the project, defining what success looks like for the business.\n\n### Summary:\n- **FRS**: Details the functional capabilities of the system.\n- **PRD**: Outlines overall product vision and requirements.\n- **TRD**: Specifies technical requirements and constraints.\n- **SRS**: Comprehensive specification for software including functional and non-functional aspects.\n- **MRD**: Focuses on market needs and business opportunities.\n- **BRD**: Discusses high-level business needs and strategic objectives.\n\nEach document serves a distinct purpose and is aimed at different stakeholders in the product development process, helping to ensure clarity and alignment throughout the project lifecycle.",
